'''
Middle Edge Solution
'''

'''
A middle edge is an edge in an optimal alignment of two strings starting from the middle column of the alignment
graph. By finding the middle edge of an alignment graph, the total area of the graph under consideration is greatly
limited. This allows for the alignment of much longer DNA strands without exponentially increasing the memory
requirements. To do this, the following algorithm splits the alignment into two parts. Starting from the source,
the optimal alignment to the middle column found while only keeping two columns under consideration at any time
since the i and i-1 columns are the only requirements to continue finding the longest path through the graph.
Starting from the sink and iterating in reverse to the middle column, an optimal path for the second half of
the graph is found in a similar manner. Finally, the middle node is simply the coordinates of the longest paths
from source and from sink, and the middle edge is the last edge travelled from the sink to the middle node.
'''


